  "prompt": "How do you determine the pH of hydrofluoric acid?",
  "response": "To determine the pH of hydrofluoric acid (HF), we need to consider its weak acid nature. Unlike strong acids, the calculation of pH for weak acids is more complex because they do not completely dissociate in water. Here's a step-by-step approach to finding the pH of hydrofluoric acid:\n\n1. **Understanding Dissociation:**\n   Hydrofluoric acid dissociates in water as follows:\n   \\[\n   \\text{HF} \\rightleftharpoons \\text{H}^+ + \\text{F}^-\n   \\]\n   The equilibrium constant for this reaction is the acid dissociation constant (\\(K_a\\)).\n\n2. **Acid Dissociation Constant (\\(K_a\\)):**\n   For hydrofluoric acid, \\(K_a = 6.6 \\times 10^{-4}\\) at 25\u00b0C.\n\n3. **Setting Up the ICE Table:**\n   An ICE table (Initial, Change, Equilibrium) helps in calculating the concentrations at equilibrium.\n   \n   Let's assume we have a 0.1 M solution of HF:\n   \n   \\[\n   \\begin{array}{lccc}\n   & \\text{HF} & \\rightleftharpoons & \\text{H}^+ & + & \\text{F}^- \\\\\n   \\text{Initial} & 0.1 & & 0 & & 0 \\\\\n   \\text{Change} & -x & & +x & & +x \\\\\n   \\text{Equilibrium} & 0.1 - x & & x & & x \\\\\n   \\end{array}\n   \\]\n\n4. **Equilibrium Expression:**\n   Using the \\(K_a\\) expression:\n   \\[\n   K_a = \\frac{[\\text{H}^+][\\text{F}^-]}{[\\text{HF}]} = \\frac{x \\cdot x}{0.1 - x}\n   \\]\n   \\[\n   6.6 \\times 10^{-4} = \\frac{x^2}{0.1 - x}\n   \\]\n\n5. **Solving for \\(x\\):**\n   Since \\(K_a\\) is small, we can make the approximation that \\(0.1 - x \\approx 0.1\\):\n   \\[\n   6.6 \\times 10^{-4} = \\frac{x^2}{0.1}\n   \\]\n   \\[\n   x^2 = 6.6 \\times 10^{-4} \\times 0.1\n   \\]\n   \\[\n   x^2 = 6.6 \\times 10^{-5}\n   \\]\n   \\[\n   x = \\sqrt{6.6 \\times 10^{-5}} \\approx 8.12 \\times 10^{-3}\n   \\]\n\n   This approximation is valid because \\(x\\) (8.12 \\times 10^{-3}) is much less than 0.1, confirming our assumption.\n\n6. **Calculating pH:**\n   The concentration of \\(\\text{H}^+\\) at equilibrium is \\(x\\), which is \\(8.12 \\times 10^{-3}\\) M.\n   \\[\n   \\text{pH} = -\\log[\\text{H}^+] = -\\log(8.12 \\times 10^{-3}) \\approx 2.09\n   \\]\n\nTherefore, the pH of a 0.1 M solution of hydrofluoric acid is approximately 2.09.\n\n**Note:** If you need a more precise value and the approximation \\(0.1 - x \\approx 0.1\\) does not hold, you would solve the quadratic equation derived from the \\(K_a\\) expression directly.",
